iscegenation carefully attends to cinematic detail, revising theories of identity and spectatorship as it expands critical histories of race, sex, and film. Courtney's new research on the Production Code's miscegenation clause also makes an important contribution, inviting us to consider how that clause was routinely interpreted and applied, and with what effects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aMiscegenation in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAmiri Baraka.  aAn Affair.  aAnathema.  aAnthropomorphism.  aAnti-Catholicism.  aAnti-clericalism.  aAnti-miscegenation laws.  aAssassination.  aBrazen bull.  aCaricature.  aCastration.  aCensorship.  aClassical Hollywood cinema.  aComplicity.  aControversy.  aCounterculture.  aCowardice.  aCrime.  aCriticism of capitalism.  aDecolonization.  aDecoy (TV series).  aDisparagement.  aExhibitionism.  aExoticism.  aFalsity.  aFilm criticism.  aFolly to Be Wise.  aForced marriage.  aFrantz Fanon.  aGreat Disappointment.  aHamlet's Father.  aHarold and Maude.  aHegemonic masculinity.  aHorror film.  aHypocrisy.  aIncest.  aIncubus.  aInterdiction.  aInterracial marriage.  aIntruder in the Dust.  aKnockouts.  aKu Klux Klan.  aLibido.  aLoving v. Virginia.  aMarilyn Monroe.  aMarlon Brando.  aMasculinity.  aMelodrama.  aMiscegenation.  aMisogyny.  aMonster's Ball.  aMotion Picture Production Code.  aNativism (politics).  aOppression.  aPersecution.  aPhallocentrism.  aPopulism.  aPornography.  aPower Hungry (Fringe).  aPre-Code Hollywood.  aPremarital sex.  aPseudonym.  aPseudoscience.  aPsychoanalysis.  aRacial segregation.  aRacialism.  aRacism.  aRadicalism (historical).  aRape.  aRidicule.  aS